CORNELII TACITI

HISTORIARUM FRAGMENTA.

1. INTEREA Judaei obsidione clausi, quia nulla neque pacis neque deditionis copia dabatur, ad extremum same interibant, passimque viae oppleri cadaveribus coepere. Quin omnia nefanda esca super ausi, ne humanis quidem corporibus pepercerunt, nisi quae ejusmodi alimentis tabes praeripuerat.

SULP. SEVER. Iiz'st. Sacr. ii. 30.

That this was likely to be from Tacitus was first pointed out by De Prato, the editor of Severus. It is acknowledged by Bernays in his Essay (published at Berlin in 1863), though incidentally, in comparison with his elaborate discussion and reconstruction os the next passage.
